description: From Middle English fulfillen, from Old English fullfyllan (“to fill full”), corresponding to ful- +‎ fill.

verbs.description: fulfill (third-person singular simple present fulfills, present participle fulfilling, simple past and past participle fulfilled) (American spelling)

entries.meaning: To satisfy, carry out, bring to completion (an obligation, a requirement, etc.).
examples: You made a promise, son, and now you must fulfill it.

entries.meaning: To emotionally or artistically satisfy; to develop one's gifts to the fullest.
examples: This is the most fulfilling work I've ever done.

entries.meaning: To obey, follow, comply with (a rule, requirement etc.).
examples: Unfortunately, you don't fulfill the criteria for extra grants at the present time.

entries.meaning: (business) To package, distribute, or ship goods.
(archaic) To fill full; fill to the utmost capacity; fill up.
examples: My lady is positively fulfilled of grace.
